sec.p:
Firstly, the distribution of temperature anomalies, expressed in standard deviation (SD) units, is analysed at each grid point using ERA5 reanalysis data, for the boreal winter (December–January–February, DJF), the pre-monsoon season (March-April-May, MAM) and the boreal summer (June–July–August, JJA) during the period 1951–2020. Second, seasonal anomalies are computed for two 30-year contemporary periods (1951–1980 and 1985–2014) to evaluate the ability of CMIP6 GCMs to describe the temperature distributions in a historical context, by comparing them with ERA5 data. The choice of 30-year anomalies over decadal anomalies aims to minimize the influence of internal variability among GCMs47, as GCMs effectively simulate large-scale global circulation patterns but exhibit limitations in capturing decadal and local variability48,49. Secondly, the projected climate change signal is assessed for the near-term (2015–2040), mid-term (2041–2070), and long-term (2071–2100) future periods, using CMIP6 GCMs under three Shared Socioeconomic Pathway (SSP) scenarios50: low forcing scenario SSP1-2.6 (Sustainability), a medium forcing scenario SSP2-4.5 (Middle of the Road - medium challenges to mitigation and adaptation) and a strong forcing scenario SSP5-8.5 (Fossil-fuelled development - high challenges to mitigation and low challenges to adaptation). These periods are widely used in climate projections, including in IPCC assessments, to represent future conditions51. The related changes in the decadal distribution of temperature anomalies are evaluated quantitatively using the parameter µ, which represents the scale parameter of the corresponding normal distribution. The shift in the probability distribution for each analysed decade, relative to the baseline period, is determined by identifying the µ value that provides the best least-mean-square fit to the probability density function of the normal distribution:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
