				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f\left( x \right)=\frac{{\exp \left( { - \frac{{{{\left( {x - \mu } \right)}^2}}}{{2{\sigma ^2}}}} \right)}}{{\sigma \sqrt {2\pi } }}$$\end{document}

HI values are calculated using daily maximum temperature and relative humidity for the 1985–2014 historical and 2041–2100 future periods, using three SSP scenarios (SSP1-2.6, SSP2-4.5 and SSP5-8.5) from the 11 GCMs selected. Here, the adjusted heat index over India is calculated as in52, which returns the heat index adjusted between different thresholds to be more accurate in the tropics at °F. The heat index calculation results from multiple regression analysis conducted by53, and it is applied by using the ‘Thermofeel’ Python library13,54 expressed as:2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} {\mathrm{HI}} & = - 42.379+2.04901523 \cdot T+10.14333127 \cdot RH - 0.22475541 \cdot T \cdot RH \\ & \;\;\; - 0.00683783 \cdot {T^2} - 0.05481717 \cdot R{H^2}+0.00122874 \cdot {T^2} \cdot RH \\ & \;\;\;+0.00085282 \cdot T \cdot R{H^2} - 0.00000199 \cdot {T^2} \cdot R{H^2} \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}

where T is the maximum temperature in ºF and RH is the relative humidity in percent. HI is the heat index expressed as an apparent temperature in ºF. We convert from ºF to Celsius for easier interpretation and comparison with the temperature anomalies. If the RH is less than 13% and the temperature is between 26.6 and 44.4 °C, then the following adjustment is subtracted from HI. On the other hand, if the RH is greater than 85% and the temperature is between 26.6 and 30.5 °C, then the following adjustment is added to HI. The Rothfusz regression is not appropriate when T and RH conditions warrant a heat index value below about 26.6 °C. In those cases, a simpler formula is applied to calculate values consistent with Steadman’s results26:3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{HI}}=\left\{ {\begin{array}{*{20}{l}} {\left[ {\frac{{13 - RH}}{4}} \right] \cdot \sqrt {\frac{{17 - \left| {T - 95} \right|}}{{17}}} }&{if\;RH \leqslant 13\;{\mathrm{and}}\;26.6<T<44.4,} \\ {\left[ {\frac{{RH - 85}}{{10}}} \right] \cdot \left[ {\frac{{87 - T}}{5}} \right]}&{{\mathrm{if}}\;{\mathrm{RH>85}}\;{\mathrm{and}}\;{\mathrm{26}}{\mathrm{.6<T<30}}{\mathrm{.5}}} \\ {0.5 \cdot \left( {T+61.0+\left[ {\left( {T - 68.0} \right) \cdot 1.2} \right]} \right)+\left( {RH \cdot 0.094} \right)}&{{\mathrm{if}}\;{\mathrm{T<26}}{\mathrm{.6}}} \end{array}} \right.$$\end{document}
